# IconField + InputIcon — Mandatory Pattern

When an input needs a leading or trailing icon (e.g. search magnifying glass), **always** use `IconField` and `InputIcon` from Circuit DS primitives. Never manually position icons with absolute/relative wrappers or custom CSS.

## Imports

```ts
import IconField from 'primevue/iconfield';
import InputIcon from 'primevue/inputicon';
import InputText from 'primevue/inputtext';
```

## Usage — Icon Goes Bare

Place the icon component directly inside `InputIcon` **without any sizing classes**. Circuit's passthrough styles handle icon sizing and alignment automatically.

### Leading icon (icon before input)

```html
<IconField>
  <InputIcon>
    <MagnifyingGlassIcon />
  </InputIcon>
  <InputText placeholder="Search..." />
</IconField>
```

### Trailing icon (icon after input)

```html
<IconField>
  <InputText placeholder="Search..." />
  <InputIcon>
    <MagnifyingGlassIcon />
  </InputIcon>
</IconField>
```

### Both leading and trailing icons

```html
<IconField>
  <InputIcon>
    <MagnifyingGlassIcon />
  </InputIcon>
  <InputText placeholder="Search..." />
  <InputIcon>
    <XMarkIcon />
  </InputIcon>
</IconField>
```

## Common Mistakes

| Mistake | Correct Approach |
|---|---|
| Adding `class="size-4"` or other sizing classes to the icon inside `InputIcon` | Use the icon bare — Circuit PT handles sizing |
| Using a `relative` wrapper with `absolute` positioned icon | Use `IconField` + `InputIcon` |
| Adding `class="w-full"` to `IconField` | Omit it — `IconField` handles its own width |
| Using `InputGroup` + `InputGroupAddon` for an icon inside the input | `InputGroup` is for prefix/suffix addons (e.g. `$`, `https://`), not for icons inside the field |
